The Telegraph - Calcutta
 SA structure sparks protests
Durban: Demonstrators invaded the field during the lunch break of a domestic limited-overs match in Kimberley on Wednesday, protesting against the new structure of South African cricket (as reported in Thursdays Late City edition). Security staff monitored the situation between Griqualand West and Border but took no direct action against the group of around 40 activists. The protestors voluntarily left the field after 15 minutes, having handed a statement to the president of the Griqualand West Cricket Board (GWCB), Ahmed Jinnah. It was a statement that said they were dissatisfied that professional cricket would disappear from the Northern Cape, the GM of the GWCB, Brian Kidson, said . From the 2004-2005 season, South Africas professional first-class competitions will be contested by six franchises instead of the current 11 provinces.  (Reuters)  Copyright 
